name: Bromo-Cresol Green
method_description: Bromo-Cresol Green (BCG) method measures the concentration of albumin, a major protein in blood plasma, using colorimetric detection. Colorimetric detection is a technique is based on the principle that certain chemicals or compounds, when they react with specific analytes (substances being measured), produce a color change that is proportional to the concentration of the analyte in the sample.

name: Enzyme-Linked Fluorescence Assay (ELFA)
method_description:
Enzyme-Linked Fluorescent Assay (ELFA) is used to detect the presence of specific analytes. It combines the principles of Immunoassays and Fluorescence detection. 
- Immunoassay procedure binds antibodies to antigens to detect and quantify proteins or hormones
- Fluorescence detection measures the radiation emitted by a sample when excited by light of a specific wavelength

name: Leishman Stain
method_description: Leishman staining is used to differentiate and identify various blood cells, parasites, and pathogens in blood smears and bone marrow samples. Sample smear is taken on a glass slide and  smear is covered with Leishman stain solution. The stained smear is examined under a microscope using oil immersion (100x objective) to study the morphology and characteristics of the cells.

name: Cyanide-free SLS method
method_description: The sample is treated with SLS (Sodium Lauryl Sulfate), a detergent that breaks down red blood cells and releases hemoglobin. Hemoglobin and SLS then form a complex. The absorbance of this complex at a specific wavelength (typically around 540-560 nm) is measured using a spectrophotometer to determine hemoglobin level.

name: DC Impedance Method
method_description:
DC Impedance method uses the principle of electrical impedance and is commonly employed in automated blood analyzers for counting and sizing cells such as red blood cells (RBCs), white blood cells (WBCs), and platelets. 
Electrical Impedance relies on the fact that cells are poor conductors of electricity compared to the surrounding fluid. When a cell passes through an electrical field created by a direct current (DC) between two electrodes, it momentarily increases the impedance (resistance) of the current.

name: Cyanide-free SLS method
method_description: The sample is treated with SLS (Sodium Lauryl Sulfate), a detergent that breaks down red blood cells and releases hemoglobin. Hemoglobin and SLS then form a complex. The absorbance of this complex at a specific wavelength (typically around 540-560 nm) is measured using a spectrophotometer to determine hemoglobin level.

name: Leishman Stain
method_description: Leishman staining is used to differentiate and identify various blood cells, parasites, and pathogens in blood smears and bone marrow samples. Sample smear is taken on a glass slide and  smear is covered with Leishman stain solution. The stained smear is examined under a microscope using oil immersion (100x objective) to study the morphology and characteristics of the cells.

name: DC Impedance Method
method_description:
DC Impedance method uses the principle of electrical impedance and is commonly employed in automated blood analyzers for counting and sizing cells such as red blood cells (RBCs), white blood cells (WBCs), and platelets. 
Electrical Impedance relies on the fact that cells are poor conductors of electricity compared to the surrounding fluid. When a cell passes through an electrical field created by a direct current (DC) between two electrodes, it momentarily increases the impedance (resistance) of the current.

DC Impedance method uses the principle of electrical impedance and is commonly employed in automated blood analyzers for counting and sizing cells such as red blood cells (RBCs), white blood cells (WBCs), and platelets. 
Electrical Impedance relies on the fact that cells are poor conductors of electricity compared to the surrounding fluid. When a cell passes through an electrical field created by a direct current (DC) between two electrodes, it momentarily increases the impedance (resistance) of the current.

name: Enzyme-Linked Fluorescence Assay (ELFA)
method_description:
Enzyme-Linked Fluorescent Assay (ELFA) is used to detect the presence of specific analytes. It combines the principles of Immunoassays and Fluorescence detection. 
- Immunoassay procedure binds antibodies to antigens to detect and quantify proteins or hormones
- Fluorescence detection measures the radiation emitted by a sample when excited by light of a specific wavelength

name: Glucose Oxidase-Peroxidase (GOD-POD)
method_description: Glucose Oxidase-Peroxidase (GOD-POD) method measures glucose levels by utilizing enzymatic reactions and colorimetric detection. Colorimetric detection is a technique is based on the principle that certain chemicals or compounds, when they react with specific analytes (substances being measured), produce a color change that is proportional to the concentration of the analyte in the sample.

name: Cyanide-free SLS method
method_description: The sample is treated with SLS (Sodium Lauryl Sulfate), a detergent that breaks down red blood cells and releases hemoglobin. Hemoglobin and SLS then form a complex. The absorbance of this complex at a specific wavelength (typically around 540-560 nm) is measured using a spectrophotometer to determine hemoglobin level.

name: High-Performance Liquid Chromatography (HPLC)
method_description:
High-Performance Liquid Chromatography (HPLC) detects the presence of specific biomarkers, metabolites, or drugs in the sample by separating, identifying, and quantifying various biological molecules in the sample.
- Chromatography is technique used for the separation of a mixture by passing it in solution or suspension through a medium in which the components move at different rates.

name: Enzyme-Linked Fluorescence Assay (ELFA)
method_description:
Enzyme-Linked Fluorescent Assay (ELFA) is used to detect the presence of specific analytes. It combines the principles of Immunoassays and Fluorescence detection. 
- Immunoassay procedure binds antibodies to antigens to detect and quantify proteins or hormones
- Fluorescence detection measures the radiation emitted by a sample when excited by light of a specific wavelength

name: Colorimetric - Pyridyl Azo
method_description: "Pyridyl azo" compound is a class of chemical reagents used for the detection and quantification of various metal ions and other analytes. /nThe compound forms colored complexes with specific ions, such as iron, calcium and magnesium which can be quantitatively measured based on the intensity of the color produced.

name: DC Impedance Method
method_description:
DC Impedance method uses the principle of electrical impedance and is commonly employed in automated blood analyzers for counting and sizing cells such as red blood cells (RBCs), white blood cells (WBCs), and platelets. 
Electrical Impedance relies on the fact that cells are poor conductors of electricity compared to the surrounding fluid. When a cell passes through an electrical field created by a direct current (DC) between two electrodes, it momentarily increases the impedance (resistance) of the current.

name: DC Impedance Method
method_description:
DC Impedance method uses the principle of electrical impedance and is commonly employed in automated blood analyzers for counting and sizing cells such as red blood cells (RBCs), white blood cells (WBCs), and platelets. 
Electrical Impedance relies on the fact that cells are poor conductors of electricity compared to the surrounding fluid. When a cell passes through an electrical field created by a direct current (DC) between two electrodes, it momentarily increases the impedance (resistance) of the current.

name: Enzyme-Linked Fluorescence Assay (ELFA)
method_description:
Enzyme-Linked Fluorescent Assay (ELFA) is used to detect the presence of specific analytes. It combines the principles of Immunoassays and Fluorescence detection. 
- Immunoassay procedure binds antibodies to antigens to detect and quantify proteins or hormones
- Fluorescence detection measures the radiation emitted by a sample when excited by light of a specific wavelength

Enzyme-Linked Fluorescent Assay (ELFA) is used to detect the presence of specific analytes. It combines the principles of Immunoassays and Fluorescence detection. 
- Immunoassay procedure binds antibodies to antigens to detect and quantify proteins or hormones
- Fluorescence detection measures the radiation emitted by a sample when excited by light of a specific wavelength

name: Cyanide-free SLS method
method_description: The sample is treated with SLS (Sodium Lauryl Sulfate), a detergent that breaks down red blood cells and releases hemoglobin. Hemoglobin and SLS then form a complex. The absorbance of this complex at a specific wavelength (typically around 540-560 nm) is measured using a spectrophotometer to determine hemoglobin level.

name: DC Impedance Method
method_description:
DC Impedance method uses the principle of electrical impedance and is commonly employed in automated blood analyzers for counting and sizing cells such as red blood cells (RBCs), white blood cells (WBCs), and platelets. 
Electrical Impedance relies on the fact that cells are poor conductors of electricity compared to the surrounding fluid. When a cell passes through an electrical field created by a direct current (DC) between two electrodes, it momentarily increases the impedance (resistance) of the current.

name: Enzyme-Linked Fluorescence Assay (ELFA)
method_description:
Enzyme-Linked Fluorescent Assay (ELFA) is used to detect the presence of specific analytes. It combines the principles of Immunoassays and Fluorescence detection. 
- Immunoassay procedure binds antibodies to antigens to detect and quantify proteins or hormones
- Fluorescence detection measures the radiation emitted by a sample when excited by light of a specific wavelength

name: Cyanide-free SLS method
method_description: The sample is treated with SLS (Sodium Lauryl Sulfate), a detergent that breaks down red blood cells and releases hemoglobin. Hemoglobin and SLS then form a complex. The absorbance of this complex at a specific wavelength (typically around 540-560 nm) is measured using a spectrophotometer to determine hemoglobin level.
test_name: Complete Haemogram/ Complete blood picture (CBP) for Leukemia

name: Leishman Stain
method_description: Leishman staining is used to differentiate and identify various blood cells, parasites, and pathogens in blood smears and bone marrow samples. Sample smear is taken on a glass slide and  smear is covered with Leishman stain solution. The stained smear is examined under a microscope using oil immersion (100x objective) to study the morphology and characteristics of the cells.
test_name: Complete Haemogram/ Complete blood picture (CBP) for Leukemia

name: DC Impedance Method
method_description:
DC Impedance method uses the principle of electrical impedance and is commonly employed in automated blood analyzers for counting and sizing cells such as red blood cells (RBCs), white blood cells (WBCs), and platelets. 
Electrical Impedance relies on the fact that cells are poor conductors of electricity compared to the surrounding fluid. When a cell passes through an electrical field created by a direct current (DC) between two electrodes, it momentarily increases the impedance (resistance) of the current.
test_name: Complete Haemogram/ Complete blood picture (CBP) for Leukemia
